                <p>The Indian electric two-wheeler market is a battlefield of competitive pricing, and Suzuki knows this. While an official price has not been revealed, industry experts and leaked information suggest that the Suzuki Burgman Street Electric will be priced very competitively to take on its direct rivals. The expected ex-showroom price is likely to fall in the range of <span class="font-weight-700">₹1.05 lakh to ₹1.20 lakh. </span>This pricing strategy would place it squarely in the premium electric scooter segment, making it a viable alternative to models from established electric brands. </p>
                <p>As for the launch timeline, the anticipation has been building for a while, but it seems the wait is finally coming to an end. Unofficial reports and sightings of the test mule suggest that Suzuki is in the final stages of its R&D and homologation process. The expected launch date is set for sometime in <span class="font-weight-700">October 2025. </span> This places its entry right before the crucial festive season, a time when consumer spending on two-wheelers is at its peak. This strategic timing could give Suzuki a significant boost and help it quickly establish a foothold in the market. </p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Diving Deep into the Specifications</h3>
                <p>While the official specifications are still under wraps, we can piece together a clear picture of what to expect from the Suzuki Burgman Street Electric based on prototype models and industry speculation. The scooter is designed for urban commuting, and its specifications are tailored to meet the demands of city riders. </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Motor and Performance: </span>The scooter is expected to be powered by an electric motor with a peak power output of around <span class="font-weight-700">4-5 kW. </span>This would put its performance on par with a typical 110cc petrol scooter, offering a comfortable top speed for city commutes and quick acceleration off the line. We expect a torque figure of around <span class="font-weight-700">10 Nm </span>to provide zippy performance in start-and-stop traffic. The transmission is likely to be an automatic, making for a smooth and effortless ride.
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Battery and Range: </span> The battery is arguably the most critical component of an electric vehicle. The Burgman Street Electric is rumored to come with a fixed, non-swappable lithium-ion battery pack with a capacity of approximately<span class="font-weight-700"> 3 kWh to 4 kWh. </span>This battery is expected to deliver a real-world riding range of around <span class="font-weight-700">80-90 km</span> on a single charge. While this might not be the highest range in its class, it is more than sufficient for daily city commutes, which are typically much shorter.
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Charging: </span>To address range anxiety, Suzuki is likely to offer multiple charging solutions. A standard home charger could take around <span class="font-weight-700">4-5 hours </span>to fully charge the battery. There is also a strong possibility of fast-charging support, which could top up the battery to 80% in a little over an hour, making it convenient for riders on the go. </li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Chassis and Suspension: </span>The scooter will likely be built on the same frame as its petrol sibling, ensuring a sturdy and comfortable ride. Suspension duties are expected to be handled by a telescopic fork at the front and a single shock absorber at the rear, providing a balanced and smooth ride over a variety of road surfaces. </li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Braking System: </span>The Burgman Street Electric is expected to come equipped with a disc brake at the front and a drum brake at the rear. It will most likely feature a Combined Braking System (CBS) to ensure enhanced safety and efficient braking. </li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Features: </span> In a market where features sell, the Burgman Street Electric will not disappoint. It is expected to come with a fully digital instrument cluster, Bluetooth connectivity with turn-by-turn navigation, and call/SMS alerts. Other features might include an LED headlight, a USB charging port, and ample under-seat storage.</li>
                </ul>
